definition.value: An iodobenzoate with a single iodo substituent placed at the 2-position.
A benzoate carrying at least one iodo substituent.
A sulfanylbenzoic acid that is the 2-sulfanyl derivative of benzoic acid.
The anion formed by deprotonating fosinopril at the carboxyl proton.
A benzoic acid carrying at least one sulfanyl substituent.
Conjugate base of thiosalicylic acid.
Conjugate base of O-methylsalicylic acid.
The N-[(p-azobenzenearsonic acid)-L-tyrosyl] derivative of phosphatidylethanolamine.
The deacylated homologue of mono(p-azobenzenearsonic acid)-L-tyrosylphosphatidylethanolamine.
Conjugate base of 5-chlorosalicylic acid.
Any substance that stimulates an immune response in the body, such as through antibody production or by presentation to a T-cell receptor after binding to a major histocompability complex (MHC).
An isocyanate that is diphenylmethane with a isocyanato substituent at the 4-position of one phenyl ring and a methyl group at the 4-position of the other.
An isocyanate that is 1,1,3,3-tetramethylcyclohexane in which one of the methyl groups carries a isocyanato substituent.
Cinchonan or its (8S)-epimer.
The (8S)-epimer of cinchonan.
A carboxylic acid anion arising from deprotonation of one or more carboxy groups of any gibberellin.
A carboxylic acid anion arising from deprotonation of one or more of the carboxyl groups in any precorrin derivative.
An orthoquinone that is the 5,6-diketo derivative of 4,7-phenanthroline.
A butan-4-olide having a chloromethyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a bromomethyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a mesyloxymethyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a tosyloxymethyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a (4-methoxyphenylsulfonyloxy)methyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a (phenylsulfonyloxy)methyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a (4-chlorophenylsulfonyloxy)methyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a (4-nitrophenylsulfonyloxy)methyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
A butan-4-olide having a thiocyanatomethyl group at the 3-position and two methyl substituents at the 5-position.
An acyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of flucloxacillin.
A spirocyclic epoxide arising from epoxidation of (1R,4R)-4-isopropenyl-1-methyl-2-methylidenecyclohexane
An alicyclic compound consisting of cyclohexane carrying methyl, methylidene and isopropenyl groups at positions 1-, 2- and 4 respectively.
A spirocyclic epoxide derived from p-menthane.
A monoterpene consisting of methylenecyclohexane having an isopropyl substituent at the 4-position.
A chiral monoterpene consisting of cyclohexene having isopropyl and methyl substitents at the 3- and 6-positions respectively.
The hydrobromide salt of poly(L-lysine).

One of three isomeric monoterpenes differing in the positions of their two double bonds (alpha- and gamma-terpinene being the others). In beta-terpinene the double bonds are at the 1(7)- and 3-positions of the p-menthane skeleton. beta-Terpinene has no known natural source.
Members of the class of isocyanates that include compounds containing three isocyanate functional groups.
An acyclic monoterpene resulting from fission of the C-4-C-5 bond in alpha-terpinene.
A substance used as an indicator  of a biological state.

The dihydrate of the disodium salt of balsalazide. A prodrug, releasing the anti-inflammatory 5-aminosalicylic acid (mesalazine) in the large intestine, it is used in the treatment of ulcerative colitis.
The dianion of balsalazide.
The hydrochloride salt of bambuterol. A long acting beta-adrenoceptor agonist used in the treatment of asthma, it is a prodrug for terbutaline.
Nonaethylene glycol in which one of the hydroxy groups is substituted by methoxy.
The hydrochloride salt of benzphetamine. A sympathomimetic agent with properties similar to dextroamphetamine, it is used in the treatment of obesity.
Pyrazole in which a hydrogen adjacent to one of the nitrogen atoms is substituted by a 2-aminoethyl group. It is a histamine H2-receptor agonist used clinically to test gastric secretory function.
The hydrochloride salt of biperiden. A muscarinic antagonist affecting both the central and peripheral nervous systems, it is used in the treatment of all forms of Parkinson's disease.

A synthetic peptide of 20 amino acids, comprising D-Phe, Pro, Arg, Pro, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Asn, Gly, Asp, Phe, Glu, Glu, Ile, Pro, Glu, Glu, Tyr, and Leu in sequence. A congener of hirudin (a naturally occurring drug found in the saliva of the medicinal leech), it a specific and reversible inhibitor of thrombin, and is used as an anticoagulant.
Any substance capable of eliciting an immune response only when attached to a large carrier such as a protein. Examples include dinitrophenols; oligosaccharides; peptides; and heavy metals.
The anion formed by deprotonating bromfenac at the carboxyl proton.
The sesquihydrate of the sodium salt of bromfenac. It is used for the management of ocular pain and treatment of postoperative inflammation in patients who have undergone cataract extraction.
A  tertiary amino compound that is the 4-bromobenzhydryl ether of 2-(dimethylamino)ethanol. An antihistamine with antimicrobial properties, it is used in the control of cutaneous allergies.
